drange‑forward crunchy guitars, upfront gritty vocals, sparse multi‑tracking, minimal compression and tasteful analogue warmth that preserve transients and punch; tight bass/drum lock; roomy controlled stereo; concise 3–4‑minute tracks that emphasize riffs over singer‑centered intimacy. Positives relative to my tastes: preserved transients, analog warmth, tight bass/drum lock, and punch. Negatives: the production is riff/guitar‑forward and midrange‑forward, emphasizes riffs instead of hooky, vocal‑centered choruses, sparse multi‑tracking and roomy stereo reduce the glossy, mid‑forward pop vocal immediacy I prefer, and the emphasis on crunchy guitars risks masking clear, bright lead vocals and hook clarity.\nWhy I choose Feels Like Today and reject Highway to Hell:\n- Feels Like Today aligns more closely with the core of my stated taste: I prioritize rhythm‑forward, hook‑first singles with immediate, mid‑forward lead vocals. Feels Like Today explicitly offers polished, vocal‑forward mastering, crisp drums and bass‑forward grooves — the exact ingredients that deliver the drum punch, bass lock and front‑and‑center choruses I want. Its radio‑ready 3–4‑minute single format and tight sequencing map to my preference for concise, repeatable arrangements (hook‑first sequencing like Synchronicity). The combination of “crisp drums” and “bass‑forward mid‑tempo grooves” indicates the rhythm focus and transient clarity I value.\n- Highway to Hell, while excellent in preserving transients and offering tasteful analogue warmth (both positives), primarily serves a riff‑first hard rock aesthetic. That midrange‑forward, crunchy guitar emphasis and the album’s emphasis on riffs over singer‑centered intimacy run counter to my desire for polished, multi‑tracked, mid‑forward lead vocals and hook‑centric pop sequencing. Roomy, guitar‑driven mixes and sparser vocal treatment risk burying the bright lead presence and pop‑chorus clarity I prefer, even though the album preserves punch and low‑